<HL>
   Letters to the Editor:
   Unbeleaguered Ayer
   Isn't Going Public
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A11
</SO>
<IN>
ADVERTISING, MARKETING, PUBLIC RELATIONS (ADV)
</IN>
<LP>
   In your July 10 Advertising column "Beleaguered Ayer
Considers Going Public," written after an interview with
Glenn Corlett, Ayer's new chief financial officer, there are
some important misconceptions that I feel need to be set
straight.
   We are not going public. We want the control of our agency
in our own hands. That's the right way to serve clients.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The article touched on the fact that we are being
contacted by agencies looking for some type of partnering
arrangement with us. Since Ayer is independent, large,
profitable and has the privilege of serving a roster of
blue-chip clients, this type of contact is not surprising.
   We are not "beleaguered." We are, and always have been, a
profitable business. We are not "reeling" from account
losses. In fact, we have gained more than $200 million of new
business world-wide, including $70 million domestically in
the past six months. And we are in the finals of a number of
large and important new business presentations.
   Mr. Corlett has been here for one month. He gave the
reporter good answers to some difficult, probing questions.
How those were incorporated into the story is debatable.
   In my strong opinion, an advertising agency is a
personal-service business whose primary motivation must be to
do the very best it can for its clients. Only a private,
employee-owned agency can totally fulfill this promise.
   Jerry J. Siano
   Chairman and CEO
   NW Ayer Inc.
   New York
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0175
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0175.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Boston Edison Posts
   Loss in 2nd Quarter,
   Cites Operating Costs
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B5
</SO>
<CO>
   BSE
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   BOSTON -- Boston Edison Co., citing higher operating
costs, reported a loss for the second quarter of about $2
million, or 17 cents a share.
   The latest quarter's loss compared with a year-earlier
earnings of $1.1 million, which, after preferred stock
dividends, was equal to a loss of 9 cents a share. Revenue
fell about 4.6% to $269.7 million from $282.7 million.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A spokesman for the utility said that Boston Edison's
revenue isn't growing "as fast as expected" and thus didn't
keep pace in the latest quarter with operating and
maintenance expenses.
   He added that while electricity sales increased by 0.6%
during the quarter, customer "fuel-charge" revenue dropped.
The revenue is based on how much replacement power Boston
Edison purchases from outside utilities, he explained. Those
purchases were lower in the latest quarter than last year,
largely because the company's Pilgrim nuclear power plant has
been operating at full capacity this year.
   For the six months, the utility earned $28.5 million, or
51 cents a share, after an accounting change that added 41
cents a share to the company's profit. The change consists of
recording unbilled estimated revenue, which "provides a
better matching of revenue and expenses," the company said.
In the year-earlier six months, the company earned $12.9
million, or 11 cents a share. Revenue rose slightly to $579.3
million from $579 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
