<HL>
   Suffering From a Lack of Water,
   They Start Plumbing the Depths
   ----
   By David J. Jefferson
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B1
</SO>
<IN>
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
</IN>
<GV>
INTERIOR DEPARTMENT (INR)
</GV>
<LP>
   Fish don't normally float in toilet bowls until they're
off to meet their Maker.
   But commodes soon may make cozy homes for marine life,
thanks to some ecologically minded officials in Southern
California who want to dump old water-guzzling toilets into
the Pacific Ocean.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Worried about the state's continuing drought, water
districts have been urging residents to install
ultralow-flush toilets to save water; some districts are even
offering rebates to residents who switch. But that has led to
another environmental dilemma as the older toilets are dumped
into already backed-up landfills.
   So the bureaucrats came up with the idea for toilet-bowl
reefs.
   "Porcelain fixtures are just as good as rock as far as the
fish are concerned. They're funny-shaped devices with lots of
places for them to hide," says John Grant, a marine biologist
with the U.S. Department of Fish and Game, which is
considering proposals from the city of Santa Monica and the
Helix Water District near San Diego to dump toilets into
Santa Monica Bay and off Point Loma, San Diego. He says a
pile of 300 commodes dumped illegally into Santa Monica Bay a
few years ago has become "a great place to dive for
lobsters."
   Harold Ball, president of the Helix Water District, says
toilets would make ideal reefs for the very reason they're
terrible in landfills: "A toilet literally lasts forever. . .
. It's identical material to a dinner plate. When they went
down to the Titanic, they found the dinner plates were in
perfect condition."
   Flush with suggestions for getting rid of old toilets,
Helix Water District is also testing a plan to crush commodes
and use them to fill potholes. Goleta Water District, near
Santa Barbara, which abandoned the idea of a toilet-bowl reef
because of cost and other issues, is using ground-up toilets
as roadbed.
   With artificial reefs already made of sunken ships, old
cars and rubber tires, "I can't see why using those toilets
wouldn't be very acceptable," says James Stewart, a diving
safety officer with Scripps Institution of Oceanography in La
Jolla, Calif.
   Even so, officials are bracing for a swirl of controversy
over their toilet-bowl reefs. "If you look at it
aesthetically, there are some troubling aspects," concedes
Fish and Game's Mr. Grant. Though giant kelp would camouflage
the commodes in a matter of years, "There's still a stigma
attached to a toilet bowl."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0140
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0140.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   New England
   Slump Hurts
   2 Banks' Results
   ----
   By David Stipp
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C8
</SO>
<CO>
   BKB BBNK
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<LP>
   BOSTON -- Bank of Boston Corp., grappling with New
England's continuing ecomonic woes, reported sharply lower
second-quarter profit of $3.5 million, or less than one cent
a share, after a $125 million provision for possible loan
losses.
   Separately, BayBanks Inc. posted a second-quarter net loss
of $11.5 million, or 72 cents a share, after a loan-loss
provision of $63.5 million. BayBanks also cut its dividend by
a third.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Bank of Boston's second-quarter profit compared with
year-earlier profit of $97.8 million, or $1.34 a share. The
year-earlier profit included a $36 million provision for loan
losses.
   The bank-holding company said that at the end of the
second quarter, its reserves for possible loan losses totaled
$892 million, or 3.91% of outstanding loans and leases, up
from $645 million, or 2.41% a year earlier. The reserves as
of June 30, however, were down from reserves of $967 million,
or 4% of loans and leases, as of March 31.
   Bank of Boston noted that "in spite of further weakening
in the real estate market and a declining regional economy,"
its nonperforming assets as of June 30 fell to $1.96 billion
from $1.98 billion as of March 31, 1990. The reduction in
nonperforming assets was due partly to charge-offs of $200
million of bad loans during the quarter, said Peter Manning,
chief financial officer. But a larger portion of the
reduction stemmed from sales of problem real-estate assets
and the reclassification of problem loans as "healthy" ones
after restructuring, he added. As of June 30, 1989,
nonperforming assets totaled $1.47 billion.
   The company said that as of June 30, 45% of its troubled
real-estate assets were in New England, 17% in Florida, 5%
each in Georgia, Tennessee and Texas, and 23% in the rest of
the country.
   Net interest revenue for the quarter was $246 million,
down from $304 million a year earlier. The net interest
margin fell to 2.92% from 3.78%, reflecting a higher level of
domestic nonperforming assets, lower interest spreads and
lower margins from Latin American operations, the company
said.
   Noninterest income for the quarter rose to $205 million
from $195 million a year earlier.
   For the six months, Bank of Boston earned $47.2 million,
or 56 cents a share, down from profit of $186.9 million, or
$2.57 a share, a year earlier. Provisions for credit losses
totaled $250 million in the first half of 1990, compared with
$72 million during the year-earlier period.
   In New York, Moody's Investors Service, citing
"disappointing second-quarter earnings," said it lowered it
ratings on Bank of Boston's senior debt to Ba-2 from Ba-1 and
on its subordinated debt to B-1 from Ba-3. Moody's lowered
its ratings on other Bank of Boston issues, affecting a total
of $2.2 billion of long-term debt. Moody's noted that despite
higher chargeoffs by the company during the second quarter,
its "aggregate volume of nonperformers remained stable,
suggesting continuing asset quality pressures."
   Commenting on the Moody's downgrade, Mr. Manning, Bank of
Boston's chief financial officer, said the bank-holding
company is "obviously disappointed" with Moody's action but
pleased "that Moody's saw fit to maintain certain of our
ratings."
   BayBanks second-quarter loss compared with year-earlier
profit of $18.9 million, or $1.18 a share.
   For the six months, BayBanks reported a net loss of $25.3
million, or $1.59 a share, compared with year-earlier profit
of $39.7 million, or $2.48 a share, including a nonrecurring
gain of $1.2 million.
   BayBanks said its board cut the quarterly dividend to 30
cents a share from 45 cents a share "to conserve capital
during an unsettled period in the region's economy." The
company added that its nonperforming loans rose to $265
million as of June 30, compared with $237 million at the end
of the prior quarter and $87.4 million a year earlier.
   Loan loss reserves as of June 30 were $145 million, or 55%
of nonperforming loans, compared with $57.3 million, or
65.6%, of nonperforming loans a year earlier, the company
said.
</TEXT>
