<HL>
   Washington Wire:
   A Special Weekly Report From
   The Wall Street Journal's
   Capital Bureau
   ----
   Compiled by Rich Jaroslovsky
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<CO>
   TAXES FREST LATAM EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS, CREDIT UNIONS (SAL)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
TOBACCO PRODUCTS (TOB)
</IN>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
STATE DEPARTMENT (STD)
CONGRESS (CNG)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<LP>
   SOUTER STARTS in good shape as he faces Senate
confirmation.
   Bush aides are highly pleased at initial reactions to the
Supreme Court nominee. Conservatives aren't thrilled but are
satisfied. Liberals are thrown off by Souter's lack of a
record on abortion; Judiciary Committee members seem
uncertain about how to raise the issue. But Bush aides insist
they are taking nothing for granted.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   While former top Reagan aide Kenneth Duberstein comes in
to steer the confirmation effort, Souter will spend next
month combing through his judicial writings to anticipate any
controversies. Meanwhile, Bush aides debate the wisdom of
launching a high-profile public campaign for the nomination;
some say that while things are going smoothly, Bush shouldn't
create an atmosphere suggesting he anticipates problems.
   Democrats play coy about scheduling confirmation hearings,
hoping to buy time to scour Souter's record, but Republicans
will soon demand a date.
                                                                                                       

   ELECTION-YEAR JOCKEYING imperils Bush-Congress relations.
   The president's attacks on Democrats over taxes antagonize
lawmakers and complicate budget talks, despite his promise to
ease up. An extraordinarily heavy September schedule of
political trips will come just as he will be trying to get a
budget agreement and get clean-air, anti-crime and
civil-rights measures through.
   Bush tries to calm ruffled Democrats by telling them he
will try to separate his general political attacks from the
budget talks. But House Democratic Whip Gray warns that "if
the president is going to run around America and score points
attacking Democrats, and then he thinks that in the closed
room on Capitol Hill we're going to sit there and do
substance, you're nuts."
                                                                                                       

   REGIONAL DISPUTES resist resolution by the superpowers.
   Soviet officials tell the U.S. they are ready to trim
subsidies to Cuba and lean on Castro to stop stirring up
trouble in El Salvador, but they assert their leverage over
him is limited. It is also uncertain whether Moscow can prod
Vietnam toward a Cambodia settlement, while the U.S. is
unwilling to pressure China into cutting aid to the Khmer
Rouge.
   In Siberia next week, Baker will press Shevardnadze for an
accord on Afghan elections -- but a Baker aide concedes that
some of the U.S.-backed guerrillas won't back any deal that
doesn't oust Communist leader Najibullah first. The Soviets
also claim they are anxious to defuse tensions in Kashmir,
but say their old ties to India make cooperation with the
U.S. difficult there.
   Baker says "we don't have any assurances" that cooperation
with the Soviets can ease these trouble spots, but "that
doesn't mean we ought not to make the effort."
                                                                                                       

   GOVERNORS WILL SPAR over S&amp;Ls at their national conference
in Mobile, Ala., this weekend. Virginia's Wilder, a Democrat,
pushes for a bipartisan commission to look at the S&amp;L mess.
But the GOP arms its governors with a long fact sheet
detailing Democratic ties to fallen thrift executives.
                                                                                                       

   GATT ACCORDS elude frustrated U.S. negotiators. Despite
the Houston summit's call for quicker action on an agreement
to phase out agricultural subsidies, the EC continues to drag
its feet. West Germany's Chancellor Kohl, for one, doesn't
want to bargain away his farmers' benefits before this fall's
elections.
                                                                                                       

   SOLDIERS TO TEACHERS: The Army asks a group of educators
to help find teaching jobs for people leaving the shrinking
military. Retiring military trainers could help schools fill
shortages of math and science teachers and find needed
teachers for inner-city schools.
                                                                                                       

   TOBACCO INTERESTS, resigned to being hit with a hefty tax
increase if there is a major deficit-reduction agreement,
angle to minimize the pain. They hope to hold the increase to
less than a doubling of current 16-cent-a-pack tax, and for a
four-year phase-in of the increase. But the chances for such
a long grace period aren't good.
                                                                                                       

   CONGRESS FACES a mess over raising the debt limit.
   With the Treasury saying it will need new borrowing
authority by Aug. 15, controversial amendments to the
must-pass bill are a near-certainty in the Senate. Moynihan
intends to offer his plan to cut the Social Security payroll
tax. Heinz will demand that the Social Security surplus be
taken out of the official deficit calculation. Kasten may
press the GOP's capital-gains tax cut.
   House Speaker Foley says the debt limit is the one issue
that could delay the planned Aug. 3 start of the
congressional recess. Ways and Means Chairman Rostenkowski
predicts that the legislation could be defeated once before
it is finally passed -- and then might only be extended for
two months.
   That would force members to vote on the issue again in
mid-October -- perhaps with a deficit-reduction accord
attached.
                                                                                                       

   MINOR MEMOS: Michigan GOP Senate candidate Schuette's TV
ads complain of Senate spending on Washington's Metro subway
system -- without mentioning that he voted for the House bill
that included Metro money. . . . Deborah Dean, a central
figure in the HUD scandal, tries something new: She opens a
Georgetown antique shop called "The Proud American.". . . The
world's only rap song with lyrics including "regulatory
accounting principles" is "The S&amp;L Rap," by New York Rep.
Major Owens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0120
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0120.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Goodyear Reports
   $9.4 Million Loss
   For 2nd Quarter
   ----
   By Ralph E. Winter
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2
</SO>
<CO>
   GT
</CO>
<IN>
AUTO PARTS AND EQUIPMENT INCLUDING TIRES (AUP)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   AKRON, Ohio -- Goodyear Tire &amp; Rubber Co. reported a
second quarter net loss of $9.4 million, or 16 cents a share,
mainly as a result of a North American automobile slowdown, a
price war in Europe and economic problems of Brazil.
   Those problems will continue in the second half, Goodyear
said. Sales rose to $2.87 billion from $2.81 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The loss also reflected charges of $21.4 million, or 37
cents a share, partly offset by a tax-loss carry-forward of
$600,000, or two cents a share. The charges include costs of
restructuring parts of Goodyear's North American tire sales
and distribution operations and closing the New Bedford,
Mass., roofing systems plant.
   In the 1989 second quarter, net income was $27.1 million,
or 47 cents a share, after charges of $95 million, or $1.65 a
share, partly offset by a tax-loss carry-forward of $4.9
million, or eight cents a share. The charges included losses
on the sale of Goodyear's South African subsidiary and of
unused pipe owned by the All American Pipeline subsidiary.
   Goodyear had expected a loss of up to $10 million for the
1990 second quarter.
   Prices for replacement tires in North America were
depressed in the latest quarter because the slowdown in
automobile production created a tire surplus, according to
industry officials. Producers dumped into the replacement
market some tires they had produced for Detroit, resulting in
widespread discounting. While major producers have announced
price increases of 2% to 4% on replacement tires effective
next month, it remains to be seen how much of the increase
they will collect.
   In Europe, Japan's Bridgestone Tire Corp. and Michelin &amp;
Co. of France are fighting aggressively for market share,
slashing prices in the process. Goodyear, which has a major
market position in Europe, is trying to at least hold its
own.
   In addition, Goodyear has continuing strikes at its
Turkish tire plants and is feeling the impact of the economic
change by the Brazilian government.
   The 1990 quarter also reflects depreciation of the All
American Pipeline System and its operating and interest
expenses, which were capitalized until the 1989 fourth
quarter. Had those items been recognized in the 1989 second
period, it would have reduced profit $26.8 million, or 47
cents a share, the company said.
   In the first half, profit before extraordinary gains fell
to $6.5 million, or 11 cents a share, from $112.3 million, or
$1.95 a share, a year earlier. After tax-loss carry-forwards,
net was $11.5 million, or 20 cents a share, down from $121.6
million, or $2.11 a share, a year earlier. Sales rose to
$5.56 billion from $5.45 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0119
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0119.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Big Board Bars
   A Broker, Citing
   Bounced Checks
   ----
   By Robert Daniels
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   MER AGE
</CO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- The New York Stock Exchange barred for five
years a broker who, it charged, bounced checks on two
brokerage firms and misstated information on
securities-industry forms required for employment.
   The exchange also charged that William F. Falbo Sr. of
Palatine, Ill., violated rules regarding margin, or credit.
In addition to the five-year bar from membership, Mr. Falbo
was fined $10,000. Mr. Falbo, who denied the charges in a
letter to the exchange, couldn't be reached for comment. He
no longer is employed in the securities industry, the Big
Board said.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The case points up the difficulty brokerage firms and
regulators have in checking the backgrounds of potential
employees.
   The exchange said that in 1985 and 1986, Mr. Falbo, while
employed at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co., wrote five personal checks,
totaling nearly $30,000, and deposited them in an account at
Merrill. The checks were returned for insufficient funds.
   The Big Board also said Mr. Falbo bought stock-index
options while he had insufficient funds in his securities
account to pay for them. Merrill notified the exchange that
the broker was discharged from the firm May 20, 1986; Merrill
said he had permitted overdrafts and abused check-writing
privileges.
   On June 2, 1986, Mr. Falbo joined A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons
Inc., allegedly failing to report his discharge by Merrill
Lynch. In June and July 1986, he bought stock-index options
with insufficient funds in his Edwards account to pay for
them, the exchange said.
   On July 8, the exchange added, he deposited a $5,000 check
into his Edwards account; the check was returned to Edwards
on July 15 for lack of sufficient funds. Edwards redeposited
the check on Mr. Falbo's request; the broker stopped payment
on the check July 22.
   Edwards, which sustained a $7,431 loss on the options
transactions, discharged Mr. Falbo July 9 for failing to
disclose a reportable item on his application and for
violating margin rules, the exchange said.
   Mr. Falbo joined First of Michigan Corp. in September
1987, allegedly failing to tell the firm that the previous
February he had pleaded guilty in state court in Illinois to
a misdemeanor involving issuance of a check with insufficient
funds. He also failed to disclose that two judgments A.G.
Edwards won against him were outstanding. He voluntarily
resigned from First of Michigan in January 1988, the exchange
said.
   The exchange also said Mr. Falbo has declined to cooperate
with its inquiries about his termination from Merrill Lynch.
But in a January 1987 letter to the Big Board, Mr. Falbo
denied Merrill Lynch's assertions and said those assertions
led A.G. Edwards to dismiss him.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
