<DOCID>
900727-0092.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   REVIEW &amp; OUTLOOK (Editorial):
   The Great Non-Litmus
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
</IN>
<GV>
SUPREME COURT (SUP)
</GV>
<LP>
   Everyone wants to know what David Souter would mean for
abortion. We have the answer. However he votes on Roe v.
Wade, nothing.
   The Supreme Court has already said it is willing to uphold
restrictions on abortions that the states, it turns out, are
unwilling to legislate. Some 40 states have considered about
300 new abortion restrictions during the past year. Only
three states actually approved new laws, and none comes close
to banning abortions. With the passion on both sides, no one
seems to have noticed that the Supreme Court has been made
irrelevant to the availability of abortions by the very force
that the liberal activist Justices feared most: politics.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Beginning last year, a slight conservative majority issued
opinions that upheld restrictions on abortions such as
parental notifications for minors. This set off an explosion
of political activity. The net results:
   Pennsylvania now requires wives to notify their husbands,
bans abortion for gender selection and prohibits abortions
after the second trimester. South Carolina requires parental
consent. West Virginia passed a law to limit public funding.
Even Louisiana and Idaho are tied in knots.
   If anti-abortion forces do prevail in, say, Louisiana, the
most that will happen is that to get an abortion women will
have to cross a state line. Anti-abortion politicians from
New Jersey to California have been scampering to muddy their
positions.
   As a matter of academic interest, it's also clear how the
David Souters of the bar think about abortion. It is
perfectly clear to anyone who looks that the word "abortion"
does not occur in the Constitution; if a Justice Souter were
presented Roe v. Wade on a blank slate, he'd snort it out of
court. Whether he'd overturn it now depends on how he
balances stare decisis with his duty to uphold the
Constitution. We can totally assure the nervous pro-choice
nellies that he will never read anywhere in the Constitution
that abortion is a crime.
   This important point should not be lost. Justice Souter
will not read through the Constitution to find some penumbra
or emanation declaring that life begins at conception. Nor
will Justice Rehnquist, Justice Scalia, Justice Kennedy,
Justice O'Connor. Nor for that matter would a Justice Edith
Jones, a Justice Laurence Silberman or a Justice Clarence
Thomas. Nor a Justice Robert Bork. Instead, they would rule
that abortion is not a constitutional issue for judges, but
an issue reserved to the people to decide for themselves in
the states.
   The wisdom of this position is already evident in the way
the abortion issue is sorting itself out once the court
started to let it. The pro-choice lobby is finding it need
not hide behind the court's skirts, and may eventually stop
talking as if abortion is some kind of sacrament. The
pro-life lobby is at least finally allowed to have its say,
and may start to calm its own hysteria. If it fails to outlaw
abortion in the legislatures, after all, it will still have a
chance to convince women that what's legal is nonetheless
sinful. This process will allow society to resolve its deep
divisions in a much healthier way than having nine Justices
weave constitutional law out of nothing.
   If Roe v. Wade is approaching legal irrelevancy, why are
the liberal activists devoting such efforts in its name? One
reason is that this case is one of the few remaining symbols
of a declining era in the Supreme Court and a fading view of
its proper duties. Liberals since the Warren Court have
regarded the federal courts as their preserve, an institution
that would bus schoolchildren, enforce quotas and advance the
liberal agenda despite its failures at the polls. This will
change as the Reagan and Bush judges at all levels make their
presence felt.
   More broadly, rumbling underneath the debate about Judge
Souter is the fundamental question of what the courts are
for. The business of the Supreme Court is to ensure justice
in accordance with the Constitution. It is no secret that the
American system of justice leaves much to be desired. It is
fair to ask, where was the Supreme Court when the police
discovered they could no longer convict criminals? Where were
the Justices as our civil-liability system imploded with
senseless and costly litigation? The answer is that the court
has ignored rule-of-law problems to find room on its docket
for essentially political cases.
   Instead of irrelevant issues, we'd like to know Judge
Souter's view of the role of the courts. Will he vote to
review the exclusionary rule that suppresses evidence of
crimes? Will he vote to hear cases that can defuse our
litigation explosion? Will he help make the Supreme Court
once again the final arbiter not on social policy, but on
law?
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0091
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0091.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Coast Savings Posts 2nd-Quarter Loss
   Amid Fears About California Real Estate
   ----
   By Charles McCoy
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   CSA GTA
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<LP>
   The national real estate virus appears to be finally
taking hold in California, and that is giving bankers and
thrift executives all over the country the chills.
   California's gravity-defying economy in recent years has
made its real estate market the most robust in the country.
Lately, with New England, the Southwest and several other
regional markets in the tank, it has been about the only
robust one left. Big California banks and thrifts, as well as
many lenders across the nation who have heavy exposure to
California real estate, have been dreading the prospect of a
crack in California, which would leave them with practically
no good markets anywhere in the country.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Fissures have now become evident. Yesterday Coast Savings
Financial Inc. reported a net loss of $28.7 million, or $1.89
a share, for the second quarter. The loss reflected increased
loan-loss reserves, primarily for bad assets outside
California but including some California problem assets too.
And Great American Bank FSB, as expected, reported a
second-quarter loss of $107.9 million, or $4.49 a share. Its
troubled assets ballooned to $1.8 billion from $929.2 million
as of March 31, in part because of a "slowdown" in California
real estate, Great American said.
   That comes on the heels of several recent disclosures by
financial institutions of mounting California woes. CalFed
Inc. cited deterioration in its California portfolio as the
main cause of its $53 million, or $2.10 a share,
second-quarter loss.
   HomeFed Inc., which reported a second-quarter loss of
$108.2 million, or $5.04 a share, said 37% of its problem
assets now are in California, a much higher percentage than
in years past.
   Banks have been feeling it too. First Interstate Bancorp,
trying to fight back from a string of surprise losses and
blunders that have badly weakened it over the past three
years, told analysts last week that its nonperforming real
estate loans would probably increase in the second half of
the year because of growing trouble in California real
estate.
   Such news has pounded financial institution stocks in
recent days. First Interstate, for example, skidded $2.25 a
share last Friday to a New York Stock Exchange close of
$34.75. It lost 13% of its market value in the two days after
the analysts' meeting. Yesterday, it closed at $34.75, down
25 cents.
   Also yesterday, Moody's Investor Service Inc. issued a
special report predicting softening in major sectors of the
California market over the next two years. It said
significant declines in asset value could appear by late this
year. Moody's recently lowered its debt ratings on San
Francisco-based Wells Fargo &amp; Co. and Los Angeles-based
Security Pacific Corp., citing potential for such declines.
   "You can no longer be sanguine about the California real
estate situation," says Donald Crowley, an analyst with Keefe
Bruyette &amp; Woods. "It is not good news for lenders."
   California isn't on the verge of a Texas-style collapse;
its economy remains the most buoyant in the nation. But the
state has been suffering from a gradually worsening
commercial real estate glut for about two years that now is
beginning to produce some notable vacancy rates.
   In Los Angeles, for example, Mr. Crowley says, the office
vacancy rate is about 15%, with enough office space scheduled
to hit the market in the next few years to produce vacancy
rates of 20% to 25%. Orange County already has a vacancy rate
of 22%, up two to three percentage points in the past two
years. By comparison, Phoenix, at the epicenter of Arizona's
real estate tremors, has a vacancy rate of roughly 29%.
   Reflecting concern about the overbuilt commercial market,
Security Pacific's Jack Hancock, executive vice president of
the bank's real estate industries group, says Security
Pacific anticipates no significant growth in its $7 billion
commercial real estate portfolio.
   More worrisome, the residential market, heretofore
seemingly on a one-way ticket skyward, has crested. Home
prices, which in some areas of the state have doubled or
tripled in the 1980s, dropped statewide for the third month
in a row after five years of almost uninterrupted increases.
House resales in June fell to an annualized rate of 443,451,
their lowest level since 1986.
   Mr. Hancock says he believes this is "an aberration" and
that the housing market is still strong. Nonetheless, he
says, "Clearly, we have slowed down in California."
   Economic factors may further damp the market in coming
years, especially if defense spending continues to wind down.
About 8% of California's jobs are in the defense industry.
Recently, McDonnell Douglas Corp. announced its intention to
eliminate 14,000 to 17,000 jobs, mainly in Southern
California, because of reduced defense spending.
</TEXT>
