<HL>
   Law:
   Calls by Juror to Drug Cartel Figures
   Almost Derail Money-Laundering Trial
   ----
   By R. Gustav Niebuhr and Glenn Ruffenach
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B4
</SO>
<IN>
LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)
BANKS (BNK)
</IN>
<GV>
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   Call it "The Case of the Inquisitive Juror," or, "Why It's
Generally Unwise to Dial a Drug Cartel During Jury
Deliberations."
   Attorneys in U.S. District Court in Tampa, Fla., are
shaking their heads over an incident Tuesday that came within
an eyelash of aborting a major criminal trial that has
consumed seven months of court time and thousands of hours of
testimony.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The case involves five former employees of Bank of Credit
&amp; Commerce International, the Luxembourg bank that, earlier
this year, pleaded guilty to running the biggest single-bank
drug-money laundering operation in U.S. history. The five
employees, as well as a Colombia businessman, are accused of
conspiring to launder $14 million in proceeds from the sale
of cocaine.
   The trial began in January. After hearing two weeks of
closing arguments, the jury began deliberations last week.
   Late Tuesday, however, the U.S. attorney was informed that
one of the jurors had apparently decided to do some of his
own investigating and had placed at least one -- and possibly
several -- telephone calls to people outside the courthouse.
The calls, according to court officials, were made to
individuals allegedly connected to the Medellin drug cartel
in Colombia. The calls were first disclosed publicly in the
Tampa Tribune yesterday.
   News of the juror's actions prompted a flurry of meetings
among prosecutors, defense attorneys and U.S. District Judge
William T. Hodges, who held a hearing on the incident
yesterday morning. The judge decided not to declare a
mistrial. Instead, the juror was dismissed, and the 11
remaining jurors were ordered to continue their
deliberations.
   Neither the U.S. attorney's office nor defense attorneys
would comment on the incident. But legal experts said the
juror's activities were all but unprecedented.
   While it's not unprecedented for jurors to take it upon
themselves to, say, inspect the scene of an accident in a
lawsuit, said Richard Lempert, a professor of law and
sociology at the University of Michigan in Ann Arbor, ". . .
I've never heard of anything quite like this."
   Testifying before Judge Hodges yesterday, the juror said
he had obtained the telephone numbers from an address book
that prosecutors had introduced as evidence during the trial.
The book had been seized from the briefcase of one of the
defendants, Rudolf Ambrecht, when he was arrested in Miami in
October 1988.
   The juror said he had made the calls out of "simple
curiosity," seeking to discover whether the people at the
other end of the line did, in fact, know Mr. Ambrecht. "No
real bad intent was meant," the juror said.
   He acknowledged, however, that on Tuesday, he mentioned to
at least five other jurors that he had made the phone calls.
   One of the jurors, a woman, told her husband about the
incident when she returned home Tuesday evening. The husband
contacted the Federal Bureau of Investigation, who
immediately relayed the information to the office of U.S.
Attorney Robert W. Genzman. Officials there called Judge
Hodges.
   "If there's a guilty verdict, you can be sure the defense
will make {the juror's actions} grounds for an appeal," said
Shari Diamond, senior research fellow at the American Bar
Foundation in Chicago. "But then it will depend on what {he}
told the other jurors."
   John Gay, court deputy to Judge Hodges, noted that the
judge had given specific instructions to the jury to decide
the case based on the evidence that was presented in court
and to avoid any outside information. The jury wasn't
sequestered.
   Few jurors disregard judges' instructions about sticking
to the evidence presented in the courtroom, said Daniel
Margolis, chairman of an American Bar Association committee
on juries, and an attorney with the Washington firm of
Patton, Boggs &amp; Blow.
   "I think most jurors are fairly compliant," Mr. Margolis
said. "A lot of people are like sheep and don't do any more
than they're told." He added, however, that there are
probably instances of such behavior that remain unknown
simply because a juror never tells anyone of his private
investigations.
   Jury misconduct of this magnitude is a rare event, said
Thomas Munsterman, director of the Center for Jury Studies at
the National Center for State Courts. "Usually it's much more
innocent," he said, such as disregarding a judge's
instructions not to drive by the scene of a crime.
   In general, jurors try to keep a distance from people
associated with the defendants in a criminal case -- if only
out of a concern for their own safety. "They don't want to
get involved," Mr. Munsterman said.
   That, he said, makes the dismissed juror's actions all the
more remarkable, particularly in light of the Medellin
cartel's reputation. "This guy's kind of brave, when you
think about it, given that these might have been nasty
people, right?"
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0086
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0086.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Thursday's Markets:
   Stocks Fall,
   Bonds Close
   Unchanged
   ---
   Budget-Talks Worry,
   Technology Sector
   Spur Drop in Shares
   ----
   By Christopher Winans
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C1
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
CDS, INTEREST RATES, COMMERCIAL PAPER (FIN)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
FOREIGN-EXCHANGE MARKETS (FRX)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stock prices edged lower amid skittishness
about U.S. budget negotiations and a downdraft in technology
stocks that triggered selling in other sectors.
   The Dow Jones Industrial Average fell 10.15 points in
moderate trading to close at 2920.79. Bond prices ended
unchanged on little activity, with traders awaiting today's
preliminary report on economic growth in the second quarter.
The dollar ended mixed, with much of the activity focused on
a weakening Japanese yen.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Stock investors turned cautious because of reports
indicating Congress is unlikely to agree on cutting the
budget deficit before the August recess. That attitude turned
more negative on earnings news from Microsoft and Compaq
Computer, which sparked the dip in technology stocks.
International Business Machines, for example, fell 1 5/8 to
113 1/8, which helped drag down the Dow industrials.
   But James Awad, president of BMI Capital, a
money-management firm, said investors overreacted to the news
from Microsoft and Compaq. Microsoft said higher expansion
costs will lead to lower profit margins, but Mr. Awad said
that comment indicates Microsoft is laying the groundwork for
future growth. And Compaq said its results were affected not
by weak demand but by a shortage of parts.
   "It's transitory," Mr. Awad said of the market's decline.
"The selling is not rooted in rational thinking. People just
don't like to see the past market leaders weaken."
   Mr. Awad said the budget-deficit factor also may be
overblown. The Federal Reserve has indicated that a credible
deficit-reduction plan will be rewarded with lower interest
rates, which would make stocks a more attractive investment
than bonds.
   "I think in two months Congress will have hammered
something {budget agreement} out that will calm the market,"
he says."
   Bond prices opened slightly higher in anticipation of
today's report showing weaker-than-expected economic growth.
But bonds eased after the Dow industrials abruptly dropped 30
points below Wednesday's close. Futures-related sell programs
caused that decline and subsequent rebound.
   In major market action:
                                                                                                       

   Stock prices fell on volume of 155 million shares in
trading on the New York Stock Exchange, where declining
issues outnumbered advancers, 778 to 701.
                                                                                                       

   Bond prices were unchanged. The yield on the Treasury's
benchmark 30-year bond stood at to 8.54%.
                                                                                                       

   The dollar was mixed. In late New York trading, the
currency was quoted at 1.6245 German marks and 150.37 yen,
compared with 1.6250 marks and 149.89 yen Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0085
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0085.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   House Approves
   Reprimand Motion
   For Rep. Frank
   ----
   By David Rogers
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The House voted to reprimand Rep. Barney
Frank after rejecting a Republican-backed motion calling for
a stiffer censure penalty for the Massachusetts liberal on
charges related to his past relationship with a male
prostitute.
   The final 408-18 roll call upheld the bipartisan
recommendations last week of the House Ethics Committee, but
the issue first split the chamber emotionally and reflected
more partisanship than in any ethics case in the past decade.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The censure motion, which failed 287-141, was opposed by
all but 12 Democrats, while Republicans lined up almost 3 to
1 in favor of the tougher penalty. "It was the homosexual
issue," said Rep. Charles Wilson, a conservative Texas
Democrat, "and in my opinion a Republican effort to say
Democrats are more supportive of alternative lifestyles."
   As the fall elections approach, the debate underscored the
politics of ethics issues this year, and both parties are
competing for the high ground in meeting promises of
campaign-finance revision. After weeks on the defensive,
House Democrats are increasingly confident of offering a plan
to cut contributions by political action committees and
wealthy individuals, and provide public matching funds of as
much as $100,000 for candidates who accept spending limits.
   Negotiations will continue today, but major elements
include a provision that PACs can account for no more than
40% of a candidate's contributions, compared with a 50% cap
previously discussed. The maximum individual donation, now
$1,000, would be cut in half. To encourage small
contributors, the measure would include a tax credit for the
first $50 donation by an individual. And though critics say
PACs will soon adjust to the new rules, one option calls for
a $55,000 limit on how much an individual lawmaker can take
from those groups, such as business and pro-Israel PACs, that
now draw a greater proportion of their funds from large
individual donors.
   The long investigation of Mr. Frank, touched off by press
reports last year, focused on his relationship with Steven
Gobie from 1985 to 1987, when the congressman paid for sex
with Mr. Gobie and subsequently hired him as a household
employee and driver. Mr. Frank, an acknowledged homosexual,
had used his position to fix parking tickets for the
prostitute and prepared a 1986 memo supportive of reduced
probation for Mr. Gobie, a convicted felon.
   The committee concluded that Mr. Frank "knew or should
have known" that the memo might be communicated to law
enforcement officials, and the panel argued that the
misleading statements in the document "could be perceived as
an attempt to use political influence to affect the outcome
of Mr. Gobie's probation."
   "That the memorandum apparently had no such effect does
not detract from the inappropriateness of communicating known
misleading statements," the panel said.
   Within the GOP leadership, the drive to impose censure
reflected the pressure of Minority Whip Newt Gingrich, who
mocked the notion of the lesser penalty allows Mr. Frank to
keep his subcommittee chairmanship on the House Judiciary
Committee. "People are looking for a guidepost," the Georgia
conservative said. But Democrats argued that the GOP sought
only a social issue for itself at a time when the party could
be forced to vote for taxes before the November campaign.
   More broadly, the Ethics Committee had an institutional
stake in seeing its recommendations upheld. And after
handling politically sensitive investigations of former
Speaker James Wright as well as Mr. Gingrich himself, the
committee leadership saw yesterday's vote as a test of its
own strength.
   "The case boils down to who do you trust," committee
Chairman Julian Dixon (D., Calif.) said bluntly. And perhaps
the strongest defense came from a third-term Republican from
Iowa. "We don't enshrine traditional family values by damning
individuals whose lifestyles are different than our own,"
Rep. Fred Grandy said. "We are here to prosecute, not to
persecute."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
