<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Conferees Agree on Oil-Spill Measure;
   Bill Would End 16-Year Impasse on Issue
   ----
   By Rose Gutfeld
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<IN>
PETROLEUM (PET)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
MARINE TRANSPORTATION (MAR)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
TRANSPORTATION DEPARTMENT (TRN)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- House and Senate conferees reached an
agreement on comprehensive oil-spill legislation that would
end a 16-year congressional stalemate on the issue.
   Approval of the measure came after the lawmakers agreed to
make vessel owners solely liable for damages resulting from
tanker spills, rather than making cargo owners responsible as
well. The conferees also settled on liability limits that are
significantly higher than those under current law.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Previously, the conferees agreed to require that all new
tankers be equipped with double hulls and rejected provisions
that would have provided for U.S. participation in an
international treaty limiting shippers' liability in spills.
That action means states are free to set unlimited liability
for shippers or other parties responsible for spills.
   The congressional effort to pass oil-spill legislation
gained momentum after last year's grounding of the Exxon
Valdez in Alaska and a rash of spills in U.S. waters in the
16 months since. Congressional aides said lawmakers hope to
bring the measure to the House and Senate floors for final
approval as early as next week.
   Conservation groups were cheered by approval of the
measure. Clifton Curtis, an oceans specialist for Friends of
the Earth, called the measure an "environmentally strong
bill." The Bush administration and the tanker industry,
however, strongly opposed the rejection of the treaty,
contending that companies will curtail shipments to U.S.
ports rather than face the potential for unlimited liability
under state laws.
   Galen Reser, assistant transportation secretary for
governmental affairs, said "we may live to regret" the
failure to accept the international accord. At the same time,
he said the administration "is pleased that this has come to
a close" and said the transportation secretary probably won't
recommend a presidential veto of the legislation.
   Under the federal liability limits set yesterday, tanker
owners would generally be liable up to $1,200 a gross ton.
Limits under current law are as low as $150 a gross ton,
congressional aides said. Limits also would be established
for accidents involving offshore facilities. Federal cleanup
and damage assessment costs, plus compensation for damages,
beyond the liability limits would be paid from a new $1
billion fund financed by a five-cents-a-barrel tax on
domestic and imported oil. That fee has been collected since
Jan. 1.
   The fund could pay out the full $1 billion for a single
incident, with as much as $500 million going to repair
natural resource damage.
   The fund could be tapped only if the accident doesn't
involve gross or willful negligence. The bill also improves
contingency planning for spills and enhances the Coast
Guard's ability to respond to accidents.
   Before approving the measure yesterday, the lawmakers
added an amendment that would place a moratorium on oil
leasing in the Outer Continental Shelf off North Carolina
until additional environmental studies can be done. The
proposal was offered by Rep. Walter Jones (D., N.C.).
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0076
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0076.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Politics &amp; Policy:
   Senate Backs
   Plan to Alter
   Crop Insurance
   ----
   By Bruce Ingersoll
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<IN>
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
INSURANCE (INS)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)
COMMERCE DEPARTMENT (COM)
EXECUTIVE (EXE)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The Senate embraced a proposal to revamp the
federal crop-insurance program and cover its underwriting
losses, putting senators at odds with the House's intention
to scuttle the long-troubled program.
   The Senate adopted an amendment by Sen. Thomas Daschle
(D., S.D.) after voting 55-42 to reject a rival proposal that
would have scuttled federal crop insurance after the 1993
harvest unless Congress found ways to increase farmer
participation in the program and cut its heavy losses.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   As senators drew close to wrapping up the 1990 farm bill,
there was a bipartisan consensus that the insurance program
was unduly complicated, actuarially unsound and, in many
states, unpopular with farmers. Sen. Christopher Bond (R.,
Mo.) complained that the Federal Crop Insurance Corp. has
become a "cash cow" for many farmers, paying $1.56 in
crop-loss claims for every $1 in premiums collected and
costing taxpayers $1 billion a year.
   But the lawmakers differed on how best to ensure that
Congress tackles the task of overhauling the program. In
1988, Congress created a study panel on crop insurance, but
many of its recommendations proved too costly to adopt.
   Mr. Bond proposed an amendment to end the insurance
program in three years, arguing that it would compel
lawmakers to address once again what he called "the
crop-insurance dilemma." But Sen. Daschle and other lawmakers
from the Great Plains, where crop insurance is popular,
warned that farmers would assume the program was all but dead
and stop buying crop insurance.
   On July 19, the House approved a $50 billion agricultural
appropriations bill that would cut off funding for new
crop-insurance policies after Oct. 1. Funding for fiscal 1991
would be cut by more than half to $101.6 million, only enough
to cover policies outstanding.
   But in adopting Mr. Daschle's proposal yesterday, the
Senate signaled to the House its determination to keep the
insurance program afloat. Under his proposal, the Commodity
Credit Corp., the Agriculture Department's lending arm, would
finance the program's operations if Congress appropriates no
funds.
   Rep. Jamie Whitten (D., Miss.), chairman of the House
Appropriations Committee, is the arch foe of crop insurance,
while the administration favors setting up a standby
disaster-relief program for farmers who lose their crops if
the insurance program can't be reformed. House farm leaders
were considering options for rescuing the program. They hope
to wrap up their version of the omnibus legislation today.
   The Senate has completed work on most of the bill, which
amounts to a five-year, $54 billion plan for U.S.
agriculture. But a filibuster last night by Sen. Thad Cochran
(R., Miss.) over the issue of cargo preference temporarily
stalled progress on the legislation. Mr. Cochran and other
Gulf state senators objected to an agreement that would
exempt Food-for-Peace cargoes through Great Lakes ports from
having to be carried on U.S.-flag ships.
   Late Wednesday, Sen. Patrick Leahy (D., Vt.) and Senate
Majority Leader George Mitchell (D., Maine) decided against
adding a provision that would have established a mandatory
seafood-inspection program. The proposal would have given the
Agriculture Department the task of inspecting seafood
processors. But Sen. Ted Stevens (R., Alaska) and other
Commerce Committee members strongly favor making the Commerce
Department the lead agency. Messrs. Leahy and Mitchell
decided to take up the inspection plan later as a separate
bill, rather than risk a farm-bill filibuster by Sen.
Stevens.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0075
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0075.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Seven Are Charged
   With Rigging Bids
   For HUD Property
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)
</IN>
<GV>
HOUSING AND URBAN DEVELOPMENT (HUD)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- Seven real estate investors were charged in
federal court here with rigging bids at public auctions, some
of which involved property owned by the troubled Department
of Housing and Urban Development, prosecutors said.
   The case is the first ever in which the federal government
has alleged violations of antitrust laws in connection with
bid-rigging at real estate auctions, according to the Justice
Department.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The seven defendants allegedly agreed not to bid against
each other, enabling them to buy HUD-owned property and other
real estate at artificially low prices, the Justice
Department said. After one defendant bought a property at a
low price, he made payoffs to the others, the government
charged. This activity allegedly began in 1977 and continued
until last year.
   Some of the property involved was auctioned by the
Superior Court here on behalf of people under the court's
protection, such as children and people deemed not legally
competent, prosecutors said. "These victims are among the
most vulnerable citizens of our city," said James Rill, the
Justice Department's antitrust chief.
   The seven men charged were: Eric Baer, George Basiliko,
Frank Gittleson, Douglas Goldsten, Irvin Greenbaum, Robert
Greenbaum and Sidney Spiegel. The defendants couldn't be
reached for comment. The crimes charged carry possible prison
terms and fines of hundreds of thousands of dollars.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
