<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                         CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   CSX Corp. -- $250 million of 9 1/2% notes, due Aug. 1,
2000, was priced at 99.62 to yield 9.56%. The noncallable
notes were priced at a spread of 1.08 percentage points above
the Treasury's 10-year note. Rated single-A-3 by Moody's
Investors Service Inc. and triple-B-plus by Standard &amp; Poor's
Corp., the issue will be sold through underwriters led by
First Boston Corp.
   Occidental Petroleum Corp. -- $150 million of senior
notes, due Aug. 1, 2010, was priced late Wednesday at par to
yield 11.125%. The notes, which were issued off the company's
medium-term note shelf registration, were priced at a spread
of 2.55 percentage points above the Treasury's 10-year note.
Rated Baa-2 by Moody's and triple-B-minus by S&amp;P, the issue
will be sold through Donaldson, Lufkin &amp; Jenrette Securities
Corp.
   BankAmerica Corp. -- $125 million of 10-year subordinated
notes due Aug. 1, 2000, was priced with a coupon of 9.70% at
99.502 to yield 9.779%. The noncallable notes were priced at
a spread of 1.30 percentage points above the Treasury's
10-year note. Rated single-A-3 by Moody's and single-A-minus
by S&amp;P, the issue will be sold through underwriters led by
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets.
                                                                                                       

                          MUNICIPAL
                                                                                                       

   New York State Dormitory Authority -- $61 million of
special act school districts revenue bonds, due July 1,
1993-2003, 2013 and 2015, with capital appreciation bonds,
due 2004-2009, were priced by a Lazard Freres &amp; Co. group.
The bonds are priced to yield from 6.10% in 1993 to 7.17% in
2013. Current interest serial bonds are priced to yield from
6.10% in 1993 to 6.95% in 2003. Term bonds due in 2013 are
priced with a coupon of 7% at 98 1/8 to yield 7.17%. Term
bonds due in 2015, are priced with a coupon of 6% at 87 1/4
to yield 7.10%. Capital appreciation bonds are priced to
yield to maturity from 7.00% in 2004 to 7.05% in 2006-2009.
The bonds are insured and rated triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                        ASSET-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   FCC National Bank -- $700 million of securities backed by
credit-card receivables with a coupon rate of 8 7/8% and a
yield of 8.907% through Salomon Brothers Inc. The offering,
through a special trust called First Chicago Master Trust II,
was priced at a spread of 0.695 percentage point over
three-year Treasury notes. The amount was increased from the
expected $500 million. Expected final maturity is Feb. 15,
1994. Stated final maturity is June 15, 1995. The securities
are expected to be rated triple-A by S&amp;P and Moody's based on
the quality of the underlying credit-card loans and a letter
of credit from Industrial Bank of Japan covering 12% of the
offering. FCC National Bank, a unit of First Chicago Corp. is
the seller and servicer of the underlying credit-card loans.
                                                                                                       

