<CO>
   F.CGE U.GEL AFRIC EUROP MDR E.DRC N.GEC
</CO>
<IN>
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   GEC-Alsthom N.V. said a consortium it leads won a turnkey
contract valued at 3.6 billion French francs ($660.8 million)
for a power station in Morocco.
   The company, a joint unit of France's Cie. Generale
d'Electricite and General Electric Co. of the U.K., said the
thermal power station will use coal, oil, and natural gas as
fuels. The plant will be situated at Jorf Lasfar, south of
Casablanca.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The power station will comprise two generating units, each
with an output capacity of 330 megawatts, and will be the
first of a series of six identical power generating stations.
   GEC-Alsthom said its partners in the contract are Babcock
&amp; Wilcox Espanola (Instituto Nacional de Industria), a
Spanish unit of Babcock &amp; Wilcox of the U.S., which is a unit
of McDermott Inc., as well as Dragados &amp; Construccionnes
S.A., a Spanish construction group.
   GEC-Alsthom said the project will be financed jointly by
France and Spain within the framework of bilateral financial
protocols among Morocco and the French and Spanish
governments.
</TEXT>
