WSJ900727-0007
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0007.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   RMED International
   Says Net to Be $90,000
   For the Third Period
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B3A
</SO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   SEDONA, Ariz. -- RMED International Inc. expects to report
profit of $90,000, or two cents a share, for the third
quarter ended June 30.
   Barry Plaga, chief financial officer, said the result is
primarily attributable to the sale of a 50% interest in a
flushable-diaper patent to a Canadian investment firm in June
for $225,000. A year ago, the company had a loss of $415,562,
or 12 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   However, RMED conceded it is having problems bringing the
flushable diaper to market. In March, the company said the
diaper would be in production in May, but Edward Reiss,
chairman and president, said RMED couldn't find anyone to
make the diaper machine. The company is now building one from
"parts of old parts," a process that will take a few more
months, Mr. Reiss said.
   Messrs. Plaga and Reiss said they expect revenue to drop
sharply this year because three new competitors have entered
the biodegradable-diaper market. RMED's TenderCare diapers,
which the company claims decompose in landfills, had been its
core product, but "we lost the momentum," Mr. Reiss said.
   In the year ending Sept. 30, Mr. Plaga expects a loss of
$510,000, or 14 cents a share, on revenue of $1.9 million to
$2 million. Last year, RMED had a loss of $1.6 million, or 48
cents a share, on revenue of $3.3 million.
   Mr. Reiss said consumer skepticism about products called
"biodegradable" also hurt sales. In March, for instance,
environmentalists specifically denounced TenderCare diapers,
charging that they don't truly break down in landfills.
   In response to such criticism, Mr. Reiss said RMED is
shifting advertising emphasis to stress that TenderCare
diapers have fewer chemicals than competitors'.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900727-0006
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900727-0006.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   BSN Investor Group
   Boosts Stake, Seeks
   List of Shareholders
</HL>
<DATE>
07/27/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   BSN
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
EARNINGS (ERN)
</IN>
<LP>
   DALLAS -- A Houston investor group increased its stake in
BSN Corp. and demanded a list of shareholders.
   In a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission,
Pelham Investment Associates Limited Partnership said it
acquired 46,700 shares of the sporting-goods maker between
May 11 and July 16 for $5.28 to $5.77 a share. That increased
its stake in BSN to 7.3%.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The investment group said it is seeking the shareholder
list to solicit consents or proxies. The group said
previously that it had discussions with Michael Blumenfeld,
the company's president, about buying a substantial block of
BSN stock and gaining board representation. Mr. Blumenfeld
owns or controls about 15% of BSN stock.
   "We're not going to give them anything," Mr. Blumenfeld
said.
   Separately, BSN reported net income of $522,000 for the
second quarter, a 13% increase from the prior year's
$461,507. Per-share net rose 40% to 14 cents from 10 cents on
nearly one million fewer shares outstanding. Revenue rose
11%, to $25.2 million from $22.7 million.
   For the first half, net income was $347,076, or 15 cents a
share, up from $424,995, or nine cents a share. The most
recent period included an extraordinary credit of $198,924,
or five cents a share, from the early extinguishment of debt.
Revenue rose 11% to $47 million from $42.2 million.
   Mr. Blumenfeld attributed the gains to the cumulative
effect of a restructuring that began in 1988 and included
plant consolidations and management changes, among other
things. Having reached its projected goal of $3 million in
cash flow for the second quarter, and with a $9 million order
backlog, the company said it expects the third quarter to
produce "favorable operating comparisons" to year-earlier
results.
</TEXT>
